offers a detailed survey of social and labour market policies since the early 2000s in Canada’s four largest provinces – Ontario, Quebec, British Columbia, and Alberta – showing the full extent to which Canada’s major provinces have chosen diverging policy paths. Quebec has succeeded in emulating European and even Nordic social democratic levels of poverty for some groups, while poverty rates and patterns in the other provinces remain close to the high levels characteristic of the North American liberal, market-oriented regime. Combating Poverty provides a unique and timely reflection on the political implications and sustainability of Canada’s fragmented welfare state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPovertyzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aFaustmann, Sam , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPlante, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRaiq, Hicham, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751349840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487513498423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487513498.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles